T1  - Understanding intergroup conflicts in tourism
AN  - 2122768906
AB  - This research note highlights an important yet rarely explored phenomenon in tourism: the intergroup conflicts between residents and tourists. A growing number of stories regarding local residents' discontent toward tourism as well as disputes between residents and tourists are being reported worldwide. Against these issues, this paper proposes a research program to advance tourism research on three fronts: to understand how resident-tourist intergroup relations and conflicts evolve under different conditions of social interactions; to examine the possible impacts of tourist misbehavior on shaping intergroup conflicts; and to explore how intergroup conflicts in various tourism contexts affect community attitude toward tourism and tourist perception of destination image. The sustainability of tourism development relies on the support of residents to deliver tourism products and services. Prior studies attempted to categorize residents' attitudes toward tourism in a unidirectional continuum, or explored individuals' evaluations of economic, social or environmental issues associated with tourism development, often explained by Social Exchange Theory or its derivatives.
